CHANGES IN VERSION 1.2.4 (2026-05-04)
--------------------------------------

* Fixed k-mer sort order being non-deterministic across platforms. When
  two k-mers had equal counts, qsort produced different orderings on
  macOS and Linux due to its unstable sort. A secondary sort by k-mer
  index now ensures identical output everywhere.

* Expanded test suite: 47 tests across all three subcommands. Per-tool
  test scripts with dedicated fixtures cover flag-level behaviour, edge
  cases (empty reads, all-N reads, no-adapter reads, sub-minLen reads,
  polyG tails, quality-threshold borderline cases, null header comments,
  known-median distributions), error paths, and stdin/-z/comma-separated
  input handling. CI now runs the full suite on macOS and on Ubuntu with
  both gcc and clang.

CHANGES IN VERSION 1.2.3 (2026-04-30)
--------------------------------------

* Fixed undefined behaviour in `stats -O` output when reads have no
  whitespace-separated comment in their header line. The comment field
  was passed as NULL to printf, producing a literal "(null)" token in
  the output and corrupting downstream FASTQ parsing.

CHANGES IN VERSION 1.2.2 (2026-04-30)
--------------------------------------

* Fixed the -g flag having no effect in `trimse` and `merge`. The option
  was documented and handled in code but was missing from the getopt
  option string, so passing -g caused an "invalid option" error instead
  of configuring the polyG tail trimming threshold.

* Fixed undefined behaviour in `stats` when encountering reads with a
  zero-length sequence (empty reads, or reads trimmed to nothing by
  3-prime quality trimming). Division by zero and a subsequent cast from
  NaN to int were both UB.

* Fixed `stats` k-mer obs/exp ratios printing NaN or inf when no valid
  k-mers were observed (e.g. all reads contain only Ns, or all reads are
  shorter than the chosen -K value).

* Fixed base-composition and Q20/Q30 percentages in `stats` printing NaN
  when all reads in the input have zero-length sequences.

* Fixed `stats -n` accepting non-numeric arguments silently (e.g. -n abc
  was treated as -n 0, disabling the read limit).

CHANGES IN VERSION 1.2.1 (2026-04-30)
--------------------------------------

* Fixed `trimse` silently discarding reads for which no adapter match was
  found. Only reads trimmed to zero length (adapter at position 0) should
  be dropped.

* Fixed `trimse` ignoring the default minimum read length of 15 bp. The
  -M default was initialised to 0 instead of 15.

* Fixed `trimse` and `merge` 3-prime quality trimming using integer
  arithmetic for the mean-window Phred comparison, causing the threshold
  to snap to the nearest multiple of 10.

* Fixed `stats` reporting mean quality as the median read length. The
  statMedian function was accumulating base counts rather than read counts.

* Fixed `stats` crashing on exit when no histogram output files were
  requested. Several FILE handles were unconditionally passed to fclose
  despite being NULL.

* Fixed `stats` writing summary output to stdout instead of stderr when
  no -o file was specified.

* Fixed `stats` error message for -z used without -O referring to -o
  instead of -O.

* Fixed several memory leaks in `stats`: GC histogram and per-position
  count histogram data arrays were not freed on exit.

* Fixed a typo in the `bfqutils` help text ("single-rend" -> "single-end").

CHANGES IN VERSION 1.2.0 (2025-10-23)
--------------------------------------

* `trimse` now accepts multiple comma-separated input filenames, matching
  the existing behaviour of `merge`.

CHANGES IN VERSION 1.1.0 (2025-10-18)
--------------------------------------

* All tools are now distributed as subcommands of a single `bfqutils`
  binary: `bfqutils merge`, `bfqutils trimse`, `bfqutils stats`.

* `merge` accepts multiple comma-separated input filename pairs to
  process several samples in a single invocation.

CHANGES IN VERSION 1.0 (2025-04-22)
-------------------------------------

* Initial release of the separate bfqmerge, bfqtrimse, and bfqstats
  binaries.

* bfqmerge: paired-end read merging via overlap detection with
  configurable mismatch tolerance (-o, -d, -p). Includes polyG tail
  trimming (-g), 3-prime window quality trimming (-t, -w), and
  post-merge quality filtering (-Q, -u, -n).

* bfqtrimse: single-end adapter trimming with polyG tail trimming,
  3-prime window quality trimming, and length/quality filtering.

* bfqstats: FastQ quality statistics including read length and GC
  content histograms, per-position quality and base composition, k-mer
  counts and obs/exp enrichment scores, and optional passthrough output
  (-O).
